article.headline: Hofstra 72, William & Mary 51
article.story: HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- Antoine Agudio scored 21 points and backcourt mate Loren Stokes had 20 to lead Hofstra to a 72-51 victory over William & Mary on Monday night, the Pride's fifth straight win over the Tribe. Agudio, a freshman, was one point shy of his career high. He was 6-for-12 from 3-point range, one 3 shy of the school record and one more than his previous best from beyond the arc. Stokes, a sophomore, reached double figures for the 34th straight game, the eighth longest such streak in Division I. Wendell Gibson added 15 points for the Pride (13-6, 5-5 Colonial Athletic Association), who won for the third time in four games after a four-game losing streak. Laimis Kisielius had 14 points for the Tribe (5-14, 1-9), who have lost nine of 10, including a 71-59 home loss to Hofstra on Jan. 5. Kisielius hit a 3 to give William & Mary a 20-10 lead with 10:28 left in the first half. Hofstra then went on an 11-0 run to take its first lead, and the Pride closed the half on a 23-7 spurt to take a 33-27 lead. Stokes had nine points in the final 10 minutes of the half. Agudio, who entered the game shooting 49 percent from 3-point range, hit three straight 3s to cap a 14-5 run that gave Hofstra its first 20-point lead, 56-36, with 9:46 to play. Hofstra's biggest lead was 69-42 on a layup by Jorge Lebron with 3:09 left. Hofstra's record for 3s in a game is seven set by Frank Walker in 1987-88 and matched by Jason Hernandez in 1999-2000.
